<POSTER> &quot;Karen Tucker&quot; &lt;tuckerv...@gmail.com&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-11-18T09:04:00 </POSTDATE>
My youngest said things like that a lot when he was 5, 6 or 7.  Now that
he's older, I see that it was likely from an exaggerated conscience.  He
gets completely incapacitated by guilt feelings when he does something
wrong, even though there was no harm done.

When he was little and saying those things, I tried not to react too
strongly.  But in certain circumstances I did react earnestly by looking him
in the eye and telling him that I loved him no matter what.  When he said he
would rather be dead, I always, always told him that I would be very sad
without him in my life.  Sometimes I expanded on that to include Daddy and
his brothers and his grandparents, if he seemed to need extra reassurance.
Sometimes I just said, &quot;You won't always feel that way.&quot;

I'm not sure that professing your love for a girl you are only babysitting
is going to go over too well. Her issues are likely way deeper than my
son's.  But you can tell her that you enjoy being with her and that seeing
her unhappy makes you sad.  Don't let it &quot;bother&quot; you.  Those feelings can't
help.  Be confident that she's not stupid and find ways to tell her so and
pass that confidence on to her.  Be confident that she is
loved/liked/admired/respected and find ways to tell her and demonstrate to
her that it is true.

It's not going to go away right away.  If she is really feeling those
things, make sure she can express it to you, without too much drama that may
be paying off for her in other ways.

Karen

