Thanks for the clarification.  I let myself get distracted and didn't
put that thought in even though I had it.  There are degrees to
anything and keeping things in perspective is the thing to do,
especially with a really big word like &quot;hate&quot; floating around.  No
need to add more to it.

My point is to seek to communicate a bit.  When a child is confiding
something that hard to deal with, s/he's asking something.  I think
it's important to make it plain that what the child said *is* worthy
of attention and not be silent hoping it all goes away, seeming as
though I didn't care how the child felt.  Something non verbal ..
stopping what I'm doing and turning my face toward the child and
listening would be simple and could lead to the child being able to
talk more openly about the trouble.  There's a lot of child abuse
going around, and I have heard that phrase come out of a child's mouth
before.  Maybe it's not as big of an issue as child abuse.  Maybe the
child feels unloved and unheard and needs someone to trust, and that's
all that's needed... a listening ear, attention.

~K~

